As somebody who’s owned 3 Acura’s (two TL’s, one RL), I’m sad everyday looking at what Acura could’ve been vs where they are now. Acura Legends and Acura in general used to be a status symbol for Luxury vehicles. Now it’s just TLX’s and SUV’s. Bring the Legends BACK!

Acura failed us (and themselves) by refusing to put V8 engines in their flagship vehicle. Even twin turbo V6’s would do they trick. And getting rid of the coupe prematurely might have led to the downfall of the Legend/RL/RLX.

Then came the RLX. The body looked big again, but the interior was actually smaller than the littler brother (TLX). Again, it didn’t have the same appeal as the OG Legend or the first RL’s, but it was cool. And now, it’s about about to be gone. Acura definitely dropped the ball. https://t.co/SuiD1M8iX0

Next, Acura dropped the “3.5”, chopped the boxy style in favor of a smaller, more curvy RL that was a complete departure from the original Legend. My cousin pulled up on me in an ‘06 and had to have one. I got the ‘09, which they made more square, but I HATED the beak grille https://t.co/5fFh8bbW67

Then Acura decided to get rid of the “LEGEND” name in favor of code names (number/letter combos) used by other car companies. Out came the 3.5 RL. Definitely lived up to the luxury part of the Legend, but not quite they same “feel” on the streets. And they got rid of the coupe 😩 https://t.co/IGWHWTFjj1

But when ‘91 hit, I feel in love! That big body sedan and even better, the big coupe were the best cars I had ever seen. And every rapper I listened to always talked about them. “I used to drive a Ac and kept a Mac in the engine” - Prodigy. To this Fay, I still want a ‘95 coupe! https://t.co/8mrnbcYcv5

The first Acura Legends might be ahead of their time. Boxy, but futuristic looking compared to most of the cars on the road. In ‘86 when they first hit the scene, I was only 4, but I remember seeing them on the streets a lot as I got older. The coupe was better to me: https://t.co/Belh3Lwx5G

Acura appreciation/fall from grace post: The Legend was just that, a LEGEND. The flagship model for the luxury division of Honda. We got some good cars after, but nothing was ever the same.
